Before we take care of others, we need to take care of ourselves. Dig into the concept of radical self-care with @lamarodofficial’s new series on Calm. 

“Many people are struggling to feel well right now,” says Lama Rod. “This series is for anyone who is interested in why they hurt—and how to transform that hurt into something that feels more balanced and connected to the experiences of others.” 

Explore the Radical Self-Care series on Calm (link in bio).

node.text:
💙 @lamarodofficial comes to Calm with a unique perspective on meditation, born from his experiences as a Black, queer male raised in the South and heavily influenced by his upbringing and the community.

In his new series, Radical Self-Care, Lama Rod shares how he disrupted harmful narratives about himself and others through meditation and self-love. “I’m a complex human being, and I bet you are, too,” says Lama Rod. “Let’s explore this complexity through meditation, and learn tools to show up for ourselves and the world around us in a way that is more honest, real, direct, and caring.”

Listen to Radical Self-Care now on Calm (link in bio).

node.text:
From our team to yours, happy #EmployeeAppreciationDay! No matter where you work, we see you, we support you, and we appreciate you today and every day.

➡️ Want a new way to show your team you care? Check out Calm for Business, which partners with organizations to offer Calm as an employee benefit. Tap our bio link to learn more and share with your HR team.

node.title: A Day In The Life 💙 Calm Team

node.text:
Life has a habit of getting serious. And that’s okay. But sometimes, letting loose and having some fun does us a world of good—literally. 

Studies show that play releases endorphins (our body’s “happy” hormones), helps us problem-solve, and improves brain function. 

Play is about doing something entirely for the fun of it. Drop a comment to let us know what that looks like for you ⬇️
